reviewText: NOT sure how much of it is truth and how little is HollywoodThe show harks back to a time when people had ethicsSo although Wyatt's fast on the draw, he does not shoot to killIn the last ep of Season II, Wyatt is trapped by 30 gunmen in a houseAnd to the rescue comes friends - these include ex-gunmen who wanted to kill Wyatt but were spared by himThey came to save Wyatt because he didn't kill them when they couldSuch gratitude is rare these daysAnd I would say anyone who expects such loyalty is setting himself up for disappointmentThis being a 1950s/60s shows, it speaks volumes to me when:Bat (Wyatt's deputy) asked why Wyatt didn't thank the guys who risked their lives to say himWyatt didn't even say 'so long' to them - they just rode away quietlyAnd well, that's real lifeWhereas a 'current' version would have Wyatt getting all emo
summary: A quick draw who tries not to kill.

Now we at least know it is airing on Encore right now so that is something. But the official release are better quality then Encore. So give it a try if you are into Westerns.

reviewText: Wyatt Earp is a true American hero, though the series obviously does not keep to real life. Hugh O'Brien is a great guy in real life and his personality shines thru. He was a hero (former Marine) and has lived a life that meets the character he plays here. I loved watching this as a child and I still do. When I watched Season 1 I felt a real thrill and Season 2 just keeps me looking forward to 3 (that I hope will be soon). Today most series are technically better and the acting/stories are sort of great. On the other hand decency and goodness is often missing. Think I prefer the values presented here. These stories hold up today and they also appeal to adults as well as youngsters.
summary: THE LIFE & LEGEND OF WYATT EARP: SEASON 2

reviewText: I watched this show faithfully every Tuesday night back in the fifties and Wyatt Earp became one of my heros.  The real one, that is, not Hugh O'Brian's version.  This was the first adult western, as they called them back then.  The other first was Gunsmoke which followed "Wyatt Earp" by one night on TV.  This was a little more "grownup" than, say The Range Rider, or The Lone Ranger, but it couldn't compare with Gunsmoke for dramatic effect or style.  Gunsmoke was real; The Life and Legend of Wyatt Earp was just another shoot-'em up that had nothing to do with the titular character than any other attempt at Earp's biography has had.  It's amazing!  After all of the movies and TV shows about this man, NONE have got it right.  I found that the vocalizations of the The Ken Darby Singers got old in a hurry, but that's the way the show was.  As for this reproductions,  the visuals and sound are first rate

reviewText: I never thought the remaining seasons would come out on DVD considering the lapse in time since Season One came out on DVD. Not sure who Inception Media is, but they apparently licensed the TV series for DVD distribution from the folks who own the rights and never did much beyond Season One. Thank you, Inception! The transfers are the same as featured on the Encore Westerns Channel. Once in a while the sound is a bit off but that's the original transfers. The owners never went back to the archival 35mm masters to do a new transfer. Their loss. Focusing on our gain, I'd like to remind everyone that the Gunfight at the O.K. Corral isn't until the final season so you have a lot of episodes to go till then. But Doc Holliday is featured prominently and the musical bridges, featuring the Ken Christy Chorus, is a novelty compared to other TV Westerns. Looking forward to season three!
Title: Wyatt Earp: Season 2 Complete
